QRP with and without NAâ€™s

We consider both the cases with and without Not Applicableâ€™s in this document. First, we create an indicator for all QRP

QRP_set <- names(raw_data[86:107])[-c(1, 2, 4, 6, 9, 12, 15, 16, 17, 19, 21 )]

Descriptives and plots

Overall

First, we calculate the descriptive statistics of the data with Not Applicableâ€™s

mice::complete(imp, 1) %>% #QRP has no missings -so use 1st imputed set
  select(all_of(QRP_set)) %>% 
  rowMeans(na.rm = FALSE) %>% #no missings
  describe() %>% .[, 2:5] %>% 
  print.data.frame()
##       n    mean        sd   median
## X1 6813 1.78892 0.7052643 1.727273

Second, we print the means and SDâ€™s for the data without the rows that contain Not Applicableâ€™s.

mice::complete(imp, 1) %>% #QRP has no missings -so use 1st imputed set
  select(all_of(QRP_set)) %>% 
  na_if(0) %>% 
  rowMeans(na.rm = FALSE) %>% #i.e. listwise deletion of incomplete rows
  describe() %>% .[, 2:5] %>% 
  print.data.frame()
##       n     mean       sd median
## X1 3033 2.097653 0.654186      2

Third, we consider the means and SDâ€™s for the QRPâ€™s for the data without the rows that contain Not Applicableâ€™s where for each row the mean is calculated based on the observed (i.e.Â applicable) values.

mice::complete(imp, 1) %>% #QRP has no missings -so use 1st imputed set
  select(all_of(QRP_set)) %>% 
  na_if(0) %>% 
  rowMeans(na.rm = TRUE) %>% #i.e. casewise deletion of unobserved values in row
  describe() %>% .[, 2:5] %>% 
  print.data.frame()
##       n     mean        sd median
## X1 6769 2.042289 0.6844935      2

By disciplinary field

First, we calculate the descriptive statistics of the data with Not Applicableâ€™s

mice::complete(imp, 1) %>% #QRP has no missings -so use 1st imputed set
  select(D2, all_of(QRP_set)) %>% 
  mutate(rowM = rowMeans(select(., all_of(QRP_set)), na.rm = FALSE)) %>% 
  select(D2, rowM) %>% 
  melt(id.vars = "D2", value.name = "QRP_mean") %>% 
  group_by(D2) %>% 
  summarise(count = n(), 
            mean = mean(QRP_mean, na.rm=TRUE), 
            sd = sd(QRP_mean, na.rm = TRUE))  %T>%    
  print.data.frame() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = D2, y = mean, 
             ymin = mean - 1.96*sd, 
             ymax = mean + 1.96*sd)) + 
  geom_pointrange(aes(group = D2, colour = D2), 
                  position = position_dodge(width = 1)) + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.ticks = element_blank())
##                                 D2 count     mean        sd
## 1   Social and Behavioral Sciences  1965 1.768494 0.6880967
## 2              Arts and Humanities   636 1.448113 0.7109644
## 3 Engineering and Natural Sciences  1465 1.756624 0.7466460
## 4     Biomedical and Life Sciences  2747 1.899659 0.6641738

By institutional support

First, we calculate the descriptive statistics of the data with Not Applicableâ€™s

mice::complete(imp, 1) %>% #QRP has no missings -so use 1st imputed set
  select(Group, all_of(QRP_set)) %>% 
  mutate(rowM = rowMeans(select(., all_of(QRP_set)), na.rm = FALSE)) %>% 
  select(Group, rowM) %>% 
  melt(id.vars = "Group", value.name = "QRP_mean") %>% 
  group_by(Group) %>% 
  summarise(count = n(), 
            mean = mean(QRP_mean, na.rm=TRUE), 
            sd = sd(QRP_mean, na.rm = TRUE))  %T>%    
  print.data.frame() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Group, y = mean, 
             ymin = mean - 1.96*sd, 
             ymax = mean + 1.96*sd)) + 
  geom_pointrange(aes(group = Group, colour = Group), 
                  position = position_dodge(width = 1)) + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.ticks = element_blank())
